{{Infobox venue | name = Stadium Municipal d'Albi | image = [[Image:Stadium-albi.jpg|250px]] | caption = Panoramic view of stadium | fullname = | former_names = Le Stadium | location = 283 Avenue du Colonel Teyssier, Albi, France | coordinates = {{Coord|43|55|24|N|2|9|59|E|type:landmark_region:FR|display=inline,title}} | built = 1964 | opened = 1964 | renovated = 1987, 2006 | expanded = 1967, 2007 | closed = | demolished = | owner = Mairie d'Albi (Albi town council) | surface = Grass | capacity = 13,058 (8,000 seated) | record_attendance = 18,325 | dimensions = | tenants = '''Racing Club Albi XIII''' (1962-), '''SC Albi''' (1962-) | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> }}
The '''Stadium Municipal d'Albi''' is a [[multi-purpose stadium]] in [[Albi]], [[France]]. It is currently used for [[rugby league]] as the home ground of [[Racing Club Albi XIII]] and [[rugby union]] as the home of [[SC Albi]]. After an expansion project completed in 2007, the stadium holds 13,000 with 8,000 seated.
== History ==
Built and opened in 1964 the ground immediately became the home of the towns two rugby clubs '''Racing Club Albi XIII''' and '''Sporting Club Albi'''. The ground is also used for athletic meetings. The ground originally had a main cantilever stand which held 1,800 seated spectators and a smaller unseated stand for 1,200, at either end there were semi-circular standing terraces. Initially called '''Le Stadium''', in 1977 the ground hosted the [[French rugby league championship]] Final despite the fact that [[Racing Club Albi XIII]] were in the final against [[AS Carcassonne]] the 'home' side won 19-10 in front of 18,325 fans, which was and still is the record attendance. It hosted its first international rugby league match in 1979 when the [[France national rugby league team]] beat the [[Papua New Guinea rugby league team]] 16-9. In 1987 the end terracing's were flattened to make way for an Olympic standard eight lane athletic track. At the [[2000 Rugby League World Cup]] the ground played host to two group 3 matches [[France national rugby league team|France]] beat [[South Africa national rugby league team|South Africa]] 56-6 in front of a crowd of 7,696 and [[Papua New Guinea national rugby league team|Papua New Guinea]] beat [[Tonga national rugby league team|Tonga]] 30-22 in front of a crowd of 3,666. The ground was renovated in 2006 and expanded in 2007 giving it its current capacity of 13,058.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Delaney|first1=Trevor|title=The International Grounds of Rugby League|date=1995|publisher=Trevor Delaney|isbn=0950998249|pages=156}}</ref>
